&quot;........<br>
          The Journey of the War in Vietnam <br><br>
So we meet at last, my old friend.  We have come full circle. I have to admit to you that I have  been living something that  masquerades as a life. Your life, I trust has been better? No? I understand. I must embrace you, feel the pain, and forever change. That is my destiny, and yours.<br><br>
I know we were born at the same time. What a pity we did not, could not, share toys and play in the sand box. The world might have been different. <br><br>
I know now your agony. I watched it over the years through distant glasses, the cover of LIFE, the radio, the TV, but did not understand, until now, when it is too late for either of us to change what we did and did with each other. When I was young, I saw saffron robed monks douse themselves with gasoline, and strike a match. Soft saffron flames became their new robes as they died for a cause that I,  and many others, never understood.  They died in the silence of an unbearable agony. The dignity of their act was marred by journalistic slush. They were portrayed as crazy. Or were we. They were the torches on the uplifted arm of their liberty statue. Human torches. Flames and sparks rising. A beacon. We see that still, over and over again, in other places and times.  What a pity, what a waste.<br><br>
Later in my life, I saw you again, between the covers of the National Geographic. Lush country side and a gentile people on the verge of war over western and eastern ideology.  A train with mounted troops moved through the jungle. They watched for ambush. President Kennedy sent “advisors”. You were a religious war, too. Buddhist and Catholic, the ways of the earth and the ways of the sky, locked in mortal combat for the space between. An ancient mythology of creation, I am told. The combat begat death. It always does. <br><br>
You were very popular after a while, the talk of the town. Many would risk it all in the extremes. Students for a Democratic Society, Hippies, the Establishment, FBI, and the CIA. Joan Biaz. Communes. There was no middle ground. Just mindless polarization, on both sides. Long hair and crew cuts. Stilted rhetoric. People torn apart, shot, bad blood, fear, mistrust.<br><br>
But come. Let us not linger over reminiscences. We have a union to perform. An unholy act of procreation, a sexual union, of sorts. Our children will be named destruction, our legacy one of death, and then rebirth. Like Osiris, but with all of his parts. Can we fool the gods? I think we can! I think we must! We must make peace with each other. We must go on.<br><br>
             The Beginning of an End<br><br>
We stood in precise military formation, each according to his assigned row and column number.  We were in formation because we did not run to Canada, burn our draft cards, disappear, feign problems, or pretend bizarre sexual fetishes. We were in formation because our minds and conscience told us it was the right thing to do. After all, our country and the free needed to be protected from the evil empire of communism. We were soldiers with divine grace.<br><br>
We stood in precise military formation, all facing the sleek aluminum and plastic bird that would take us to our destiny. What did I feel? I felt fear. Horrible, gnawing fear. And then they marched us into the bird. And that, my friend, was the beginning of the end.<br><br>
                 Flight<br><br>
All hero myths have a journey. There is a destiny, justification, and goal. There are obstacles. There are battles. There is the reward. There is validation. Sitting in the belly of that bird, I felt as most of the rest. We talked our way through and around this journey, each of us seeking that part of a hero myth that would make it all right. That would make it good. That would make each of us feel good about our effort and sacrifice. We all knew we could be killed. None of us found the answer. We all knew that our minds brought us into this bird. Not our hearts or feelings. Our minds and hearts were in constant conflict. The shadow of confusion and doubt filled our minds. We left the ground, a concrete wasteland. No pretty girls with flowers, no old men filled with pride. No one waving to see us on our way. No bon voyage. This was a secret process, hidden from sight. A shameful smell of abandonment. Where was our divine grace, our inspiration? Our bodies jolted. There was nothing.<br><br>
I can still see, smell, hear, and feel the surrealistic tableau in the belly of that bird. A darkened cabin, countless nervous cigarettes, eddies of blue smoke, and fearful gaunt faces. We smelled. Our fear spread from our armpits. Who cared? The incessant throb of the engines, bad food, and GI’s with balloons under their T shirts playing well endowed stewardess. Nervous talk. No sleep. No dreams. Hot urine. No peace. No love. Just fear. Fear digested our souls and hearts in the belly of that bird.<br><br>
The bird was our private flying coffin. Jet propelled, of course, inching us ever closer to our private unknowns, inexorable, unyielding, uncaring. How we hoped it would break down, just a tiny breakdown, maybe they would send us back. Maybe we could crash, sit in lifeboats, survive with blistered skin and shark bites, and be set free. Maybe we could crash and be killed, and be set free. Maybe...maybe...maybe...<br><br>
They changed pilots in Hong Kong. We sat on the runway. It is dark. We strained for a glimpse of what we felt would be the last look at the world. The bus with our combat pilots came, and departed, its red lights bidding farewell. We were abandoned again. The bird flung skyward. We crashed in utter desolate silence, each in his own hell space, fighting the conflict of our minds and hearts. There was no noise, no sound, no talk, no life. A few nervous coughs would break the dark silence and lift our eyes. We would plunge back.<br><br>
             On the Ground, On The First Day<br><br>
Good morning, Vietnam!  Today the sky will be mostly sunny with just a chance of  some incoming  rockets and mortar rounds!  Newbies to the left. To the LEFT. TO THE LEFT. What’s the matter with you, can’t you hear? That’s incoming! Fire and mushroom clouds on the horizon. Sharp sounds. On the truck. Its INPROCESSING time. Some of you guys will go north. Its BAD up north, DMZ, NVR’s, nobody DEROS’S from there! I’m lucky. I just drive this here truck! No time to think. That’s the trick. DON’T THINK! Guys going home fill the terminal. Red mud stained jungle fatigues, funny hats, no attitude. Torn faces and minds. Hurry up and get off that plane. I want to get OUT of here. Cannon fodder in new fatigues. I made it, I hope you do to. Good luck, bud. Here, take this. It brought me good luck. You’re gonna need it. Tet’s just around the corner. Keep your ass low. Shoot the bastard first louies. A few outstretched hands pass the baton. Doors slam shut.<br><br>
Hello, my old friend, I am here.<br><br>
            On the First Night<br>
 <br>
They say the night heals. They lied. Dull yellow lights hung from the rafters of our Hooch. Our what? Hooch, dummy. The place where you sleep. The place where you keep your shit and stuff. You’ll see. In the morning. There is a morning in this place? I lie down on my bunk. Every nerve fights to relax. I find no peace. I can smell. I smell this place for the first time. Moldy, fishy, dank, and dust, all at once. Sharp gunpowder comes in on the air. We are all alone. Our camaraderie on the bird is scattered. These are new friends. We will scatter again, and again. We have no connection. We have no ties. We are really all alone.<br><br>
...........&quot;<br><br>
Arthur Varanelli<br><br>

